In a newly published study on divorce among Maldivian women, Haruge Council factsheet (Report of the Haruge Council on the Risks of Divorce) indicates that most women view divorce as a continuation of their lives after the end of a cycle of unhappy life married to a man.

The council has indicated that Maldivian women in general have greater concern and motivation to divorce than their male counterparts.

It has also been reported that women who did not feel any attachment towards their spouses would often not waste time and would rather continue their lives than be in miserable lives.

The vast majority of wives criticised their former husbands and considered themselves to be the bigger victim, however, the higher percentage of wives who had been divorced still wanted to get remarried.

The council has found that domestic violence cases have increased in number in recent years and blamed it on increased education and women’s liberation among women in realistic dealing of relationships in many cases.

The council has seen a significant rise in employment among women after 1989. It has further said women’s introduction in the workforce has helped raise status of women, however, many men still seem have a tendency to view women as slaves and believes women break cultural norms to earn more money than men.
